<figureCitation id="3165F44ECEAA986D245C2B5F931B059C" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F5978765" captionText="Figure 4. Habitus illustrations of Nepomorpha of Mindoro A. Ranatra sp. (R. gracilis group); B. Ochterus polhemusi; C. Asthenocoris luzonensis paradisianus; D. Aphelocheirus (s. str) freitagi; E. Anisops kuroiwae; F. Anisops rhomboides; G. Enithares martini mindoroensis; H. Hydrotrephes stereoides mindoroensis. Scale bars A 10 mm B-H 1 mm. A &amp; C © NHMW Hemiptera Image Collection / photo: H. Bruckner, printed with permission." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.8.e56883.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/467223" pageId="0" pageNumber="56883">4</figureCitation>
D) is endemic to Mindoro and was previously only known from its type locality, Malayas River in Victoria, Oriental Mindoro (
<bibRefCitation id="6DA4E28B378668340267A0727EF1FBCB" author="Zettel, H." journalOrPublisher="Linzer biologische Beitraege" pageId="0" pageNumber="56883" pagination="1353 - 1362" refId="B5979759" refString="Zettel, H., Pangantihon, C. V., 2010. Aphelocheirus (s.str.) freitagi nov. sp. from Mindoro Island and additional notes on Philippine Aphelocheiridae (Heteroptera). In: Linzer biologische Beitraege.: 1353 - 1362" title="Aphelocheirus (s. str.) freitagi nov. sp. from Mindoro Island and additional notes on Philippine Aphelocheiridae (Heteroptera)" volumeTitle="Linzer biologische Beitraege." year="2010">Zettel and Pangantihon 2010</bibRefCitation>
). Here we present the first records from Baco and Roxas (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="6D9DD17522A66B8A751D76FE869A4D15" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F5979082" captionText="Figure 5. Distribution of the collecting sites of Nepomorpha material treated in this study." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.8.e56883.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/467245" pageId="0" pageNumber="56883">5</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
